{{about|traversal of a telecommunications network|traversal of a computer network|Hop (networking)}}
{{For|waveforms in a frequency-hopping spread spectrum system|Frequency-hopping spread spectrum}}
In [[telecommunication]], a '''hop''' is a portion of a signal's journey from source to receiver. Examples include:
#The excursion of a [[radio wave]] from the [[Earth]] to the [[ionosphere]] and back to the Earth.  The number of hops indicates the number of reflections from the ionosphere.<ref>[[Federal Standard 1037C]]</ref>
#A similar excursion from an [[earth station]] to a [[communications satellite]] to another station, counted similarly except that if the return trip is not by satellite, then it's only a half hop.
#In [[routing]], a hop is the step from one [[Router (computing)|router]] to the next, on the path of a [[Packet (information technology)|packet]] on any communications network. On the [[Internet]] the hops a packet takes may be discovered with [[Ping (networking utility)|ping]]s or [[traceroute]]s. The hop count is the total number of steps along the path from source to sink. In this context, the term "hop" is sometimes said to be an acronym for "hand-over point".

